    }
}
```

But then at line 215-216:
```cpp
int processed = jpeg_write_raw_data(cinfo, need_padding ? planes_intrm : planes,
                                    kCompressBatchSize);  // Passes 16!
```

The problem: `cb` and `cr` arrays are declared as `JSAMPROW cb[kCompressBatchSize / 2]` (8 elements), but `jpeg_write_raw_data()` is called with `kCompressBatchSize` (16). This means `jpeg_write_raw_data()` will try to access `cb[8]` through `cb[15]`, which are **out of bounds**!

This is a stack buffer overflow! The arrays `cb` and `cr` only have 8 elements each, but `jpeg_write_raw_data()` expects 16 elements when called with `num_rows=16`.

Actually wait, looking more carefully - the `planes` array is `JSAMPARRAY planes[3]{y, cb, cr}`. When passed to `jpeg_write_raw_data()`, it passes the pointer to the array of 3 color component planes. Each plane (y, cb, cr) is itself an array of row pointers.

The issue is that `cb` and `cr` only have 8 elements, but `jpeg_write_raw_data()` with `num_rows=16` will try to read 16 row pointers from each plane!

This is the sanitizer crash - a stack buffer overflow when accessing `cb[8]` through `cb[15]`.

